                            Thirty years back or was it forty years as young girl in LSR I went through protests on rape ( famous Billa-Ranga case); we did street plays on dowry deaths- bride burning; we protested the molestation of girls by Delhi University boys before Holi; we struggled through riding on DTC buses where we had to endure pinching, rubbing, stares, lewd remarks; favourite pasttime of delhi cyclists at that time was to catch girls dupattas as they walked by.......and now I see the saga still continues.......girls will protest, women will protest and then things will die down. How does one change centuries of archaic mindset. I guess protesting will not work - every women in India maybe go on strike ?! Unrealistic thought - but nothing seems to shake the medieval mindset of our men and even, sad to say many of our women too! Sad to see that the struggle continues and god forbid how many centuries more would the women of India have to endure this attitude. I guess we are all waiting for that Woman Avatar who will eventually take charge and stand up and lead us to change. Again wishful thinking. I have a sneaky feeling that the men, our leaders, think this is a huge joke. Watch think let them protest, humour them- eventually they will stop or lose interest. Do we ( women) have the courage to prove them wrong? I saw and met girls back then who went with us in all our anti anti dowry rallies, but quietly agreed to millions as dowry at the time of marriage. They didn't want to be left on the shelf. True they had a point; societal pressure, parents emotional blackmail and pressure sometimes gets too much. The struggle is not just about rape - the struggle for respect and dignity and the need for society to recognise that women/girls are individuals are human beings who have the right to choose - to lead their lives as they choose; just like men do.
