Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=294127" target="_blank">Krishna Tennety</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            I see that almost all reactions to the airing of this documentary are also suggesting a solution - mostly of "banning". Either the documentary itself, or like this writer says, the people who have this mindset. The problem is way too complicated to suggest such knee jerk solutions.All of us must understand that India is NOT like the US, UK or any of the western countries. It never was, it never will be. This country is one of the oldest civilisations in the world and has a certain culture associated with it. The question is not whether the culture is right or wrong : it exists. It is an irrevocable fact. Hence, any solution to the growing menace of assaults on women (sexual or otherwise), needs to be seen with this perspective. We have to have a group of intellectuals who should brainstorm and deliberate to come up with out of the box solutions to root out this problem.We can keep shouting ourselves hoarse about a male dominated society or a patriarchical system, but it will not change overnight!If a mindset is endemic in a society, we should accept it exists and seek ways to bring about a systematic change. This may take years. The fact of the matter is, the chasm between our "culture" and modernism is growing day by day, particularly at the turn of the twenty first century. While the traditionalists are sticking by their beliefs and convictions, the women of today are moving further and further away towards "modernism". The need of the hour is to bridge this gap. Therein lays the solution.
